@gordlittle OnlyFans will grow its brand off sex workers, then try to kick sex workers off. Tumblr banned all adult blogs. Paypal will steal your money if you're selling adult content. Steam only started letting on adult games recently despite them always being a big seller.

@gordlittle Hahaha. Purity culture is sex being treated as more dangerous than violence. i.e. erotica is usually hidden on Amazon, but you can read about real life serial killers. Apple not allowing erotic books etc.

It also means that people tend to be more broad about triggers (i.e. dark romance, which could mean multiple things and is a large spectrum of romance), so it's harder to find the content you want to read, and harder to avoid content you don't want to read.

Amazon prefers that you obfuscate the potentially triggering content in your marketing (cover/title/blurb) because purity culture states that it's more offensive to know precisely what a book is about than it is to go in without realizing it could be triggering.

Today is bittersweet, but I know the new board will continue to advocate, fundraise, grow, and develop the @SJSOWC to the benefit of all Newfoundlanders and Labradoreans.

To all my sisters and comrades in the struggle, I wish you bread and roses.

It can be hard work. It requires tough conversations. A lot of self reflection, reading, learning, struggling, and growing.

I'm immensely proud of my time on the board, of my volunteer work, and the things I've achieved. I am filled with gratitude I had this chance.

If you can volunteer your time and energy, and you find the right people, the right organization, you'll know it.

We can't individually change the whole world, not for every body. But for a few people, you can change their whole world.

If I can leave you with anything, it's this:
If you're in government, multi year funding is vital for the stability of these programs.
If you're not in government, donations and interpersonal donation drives are amazing. They can stretch a dollar far.
And lastly,

Serving an organization that does so much important work has been a ray of hope in my darkest times. If you're looking at the @SJSOWC from the outside, you don't know a tenth of the impact it has on the people of St. John's, across the province, across Canada.

I moved into the Board of Directors at the end of 2017, and since then, I've learned a lot about what it means to be a valued director, about governance, about finances, about the role of a board, and how to operate as a team.

I started volunteering with @sexworkoutreach in 2016, during their first drop in dinner. It was a privilege to be allowed into a space of vulnerability, honesty, and power. I was thrilled to be connected with people who shared my values, and learn from them.

Today is my last day serving on the Board of Directors for the @SJSOWC and I'm crying, my heart is so full and so heavy. It has been such an honour, and I'm so proud of the staff and volunteers, and all they achieve, every day.

@jnp709 @blkgirllostkeys Thank you!

@pettyprozzie Pomodoro doesn't always work for me, but sometimes it helps me trick myself into working for 'just 25 minutes'. I think the important thing is to be committed to those 25 minutes, and have an intention set for it. Sometimes it doesn't work, and the focus won't come, but I tried.

@pettyprozzie I might also sometimes have a pad of paper there to write down things that come up for me that might distract me. So if I'm writing, and I think, "what will I do for supper?" I'll write that down and come back to it on the break.

@pettyprozzie I also find it best to have a plan for the breaks. Still no twitter / things that make me time blind. I can stand up, go pee, grab water, stretch, look outside, open the window, etc. But nothing that might grab my attention and distract me from getting back to the task.

@pettyprozzie I also find it works best if I set the task, and the reason why I want to do that task, ahead of time, and have a place to start. Trying to 'manufacture interest' in the task at hand, or find some way to spark curiosity, can also help me.

@pettyprozzie I find it works best when I remove all other distractions. Like okay, maybe I'll sit there and not work, but for 25 minutes, I'm not allowed on twitter/playing games/chatting in discord etc. So then work sounds a lot more interesting than doing nothing.

@hopeless_hooker @pettyprozzie And with ADHD I always feel like I'm running behind, that I always have to play catch up, so I can't afford to stop when I've gotten started. It's a big pain point for me.

@hopeless_hooker @pettyprozzie This is so me, and my occupational therapist is advising that I should explore breaking this habit. She worries that setting up this expectation that once I start I can't stop adds to the all or nothing thinking. But I love the feeling of productivity on hyperfocus days.
I can't deal with shrill alarms like the usual egg timers, I'd prefer something gentle with a rising volume. Even better if there's a visual cue that times up followed by audio after a delay.

ADHD friends: I'm looking for a timer, preferably not an app though I'm interested in those too.
Requirements:
Easy to use / move around (so battery operated)
Won't scare the bejesus out of me when it goes off
Something pretty / colourful / visual is a bonus

I think it's a lot easier to start something new when you're planning on replacing something old with it. Otherwise you set yourself up for frustration of not having enough time for your new pursuit.
And this is true for all things. Going back to school? Learning a new skill? Pursuing artistic development? Writing a book? How are you going to make time?

It's one thing to say you're going to exercise more, say, but what are you going to give up to make the time for it? If you plan on exercising in the morning, but you want to give up something in the afternoon or evening, it might be better to exercise at that time.
I think one very important consideration for when you're thinking of taking up a new habit / hobby, is what are you going to stop doing to make time for it?

The reason I've seen such healing in my own journey is:
1) persistence & prioritization of my healing
2) reading/practicing skills between sessions
3) self reflection
4) a supportive partner
5) the intensity of my mental illnesses
6) medication & therapy & financial security

If you have a mental illness that is not caused by a temporary life change, you likely already have a pretty impressive repertoire of coping mechanisms you've been using while on the waitlist. Most people seeking general therapy don't need therapy by the time they get the appt.

Anyone who suggests that you can go to therapy once a week for mental illness and be healed is naïve at best, actively harmful at worst. That type of therapy works best for people with temporarily stressful life changes who need someone to listen to & build coping skills.

The people who see the best results from therapy are the people who make therapy a part of their lifestyle. Reading books, practicing coping methods, practicing self care and self soothing and self compassion are vital for cptsd/depression/anxiety. https://t.co/iR5RwaLQst
